issue.title: Fix fetch invoices type error
issue.body: Fixes "TypeError: Failed to fetch" by ensuring API routes run on Node.js runtime and removing a client-side Node.js import. The "Failed to fetch" error was caused by Next.js API routes, which utilize Prisma and JWT, implicitly attempting to run on the unsupported Edge runtime. Explicitly setting `export const runtime = "nodejs";` for these routes forces them to use the Node.js runtime, resolving the underlying crash. Additionally, an unused Node.js-specific `process` import was removed from a client-side component to prevent potential browser-side issues. ---

review.body:
## Pull Request Overview

This PR adds D3.js-based treemap visualization generation to the coverage action, creating visual representations of code coverage for changed files. The treemap shows functions/methods with color-coded coverage status (green for fully covered, orange for partial, red for uncovered) and uploads the generated PNG as a GitHub artifact.

- Implements treemap generation using D3.js and Sharp for PNG conversion
- Adds artifact service for uploading and managing treemap files
- Integrates treemap visualization into PR comments with download links

### Reviewed Changes

Copilot reviewed 9 out of 10 changed files in this pull request and generated 8 comments.

| src/artifactService.test.ts | Test coverage for artifact upload and cleanup functionality |
| src/prComment.ts | Enhanced PR comment generation to include treemap artifact information |
| src/prComment.test.ts | Updated tests to cover artifact integration in comments |
| src/index.ts | Main integration point adding treemap generation to the action workflow |
| src/index.test.ts | Test coverage for new treemap workflow integration |
| package.json | Added dependencies for D3.js, Sharp, and JSDOM visualization libraries |
</details>

review.body:
## Pull Request Overview

This PR adds D3.js-based treemap visualization generation to the coverage action, creating visual representations of code coverage for changed files. The treemap shows functions/methods with color-coded coverage status (green for fully covered, orange for partial, red for uncovered) and uploads the generated PNG as a GitHub artifact.

- Implements treemap generation using D3.js and Sharp for PNG conversion
- Adds artifact service for uploading and managing treemap files
- Integrates treemap visualization into PR comments with download links

### Reviewed Changes

Copilot reviewed 9 out of 10 changed files in this pull request and generated 8 comments.

<details>
<summary>Show a summary per file</summary>

| File | Description |
| ---- | ----------- |
| src/treemapGenerator.ts | Core treemap generation logic using D3.js to create coverage visualizations |
| src/treemapGenerator.test.ts | Comprehensive test coverage for treemap data generation and PNG creation |
| src/artifactService.ts | Service for uploading artifacts and managing temporary files |
| src/artifactService.test.ts | Test coverage for artifact upload and cleanup functionality |
| src/prComment.ts | Enhanced PR comment generation to include treemap artifact information |
| src/prComment.test.ts | Updated tests to cover artifact integration in comments |
| src/index.ts | Main integration point adding treemap generation to the action workflow |
| src/index.test.ts | Test coverage for new treemap workflow integration |
| package.json | Added dependencies for D3.js, Sharp, and JSDOM visualization libraries |
</details>

pull_request.title: Fix fetch invoices type error
pull_request.body: Fixes "TypeError: Failed to fetch" by ensuring API routes run on Node.js runtime and removing a client-side Node.js import. The "Failed to fetch" error was caused by Next.js API routes, which utilize Prisma and JWT, implicitly attempting to run on the unsupported Edge runtime. Explicitly setting `export const runtime = "nodejs";` for these routes forces them to use the Node.js runtime, resolving the underlying crash. Additionally, an unused Node.js-specific `process` import was removed from a client-side component to prevent potential browser-side issues. ---

feat: Add sidebar toggle and GPS breadcrumbs

This commit introduces two significant user experience improvements to the main interface.

1.  **Collapsible Sidebar Toggle**: The activity bar buttons (`Guides`, `Map`) now also function as a toggle for the sidebar. Clicking the currently active icon will collapse the sidebar, and clicking any icon will expand it if it's collapsed. This provides more control over the screen real estate.
2.  **GPS Breadcrumbs**: The "Live GPS Mode" now includes a breadcrumb trail feature. As the user moves, a red path is drawn on the map, showing their traveled route. This trail is automatically cleared when GPS tracking is stopped.

- **`js/main.js`**: Logic updated for the sidebar toggle and to implement the breadcrumb trail.
- **`css/style.css`**: Styles updated to support the collapsible sidebar on all screen sizes.
